t-SNE with Clustar Output¶

Clustar returns groups containing each celestial object detected within FITS images. Here, that output is used as the input to a t-SNE model that maps each image to a low-dimensional representation.

Setup¶

Set options and directory containing images; import packages. Option im_type specifies whether to use original images or residuals from a bivariate Gaussian fit.

In [1]:
im_type = 'original'
# im_type = 'residuals'

In [7]:
#get size of largest image

size = 0
for group in output:
    if np.shape(group['data'])[0] > size:
        size = np.shape(group['data'])[0]
In [8]:
#resize groups to match largest image
#using skimage resize function

data = np.empty([len(output)*4, size, size]) # *4 to make room for data augmentation later
file_list = ['']*(len(output)*4)
flag_list = ['']*(len(output)*4)

i = 0
for group in output:
    if im_type == 'residuals':
        resized = resize(np.array(group['residuals']), (size, size), anti_aliasing=True)
    else:
        resized = resize(np.array(group['data']), (size, size), anti_aliasing=True)
    data[i] = resized
    file_list[i] = group['file']
    flag_list[i] = group['flag']
    i += 1
In [10]:
#data augmentation (rotations of 90, 180, 270 degrees)
#used combinations of numpy transpose and flip to achieve rotations for speed

for group in range(len(output)):
    rot90 = np.flip(data[group], axis = 1).T
    rot180 = np.flip(data[group])
    rot270 = np.flip(data[group], axis = 0).T

    data[i] = rot90
    file_list[i] = output[group]['file']
    flag_list[i] = output[group]['flag']
    i += 1
    data[i] = rot180
    file_list[i] = output[group]['file']
    flag_list[i] = output[group]['flag']
    i += 1
    data[i] = rot270
    file_list[i] = output[group]['file']
    flag_list[i] = output[group]['flag']
    i += 1

TSNE¶

I used a tutorial from a machine learning workshop by the American Astronomical Society (AAS) to get started with t-SNE. I also relied on the scikit-learn documentation and this How to Use t-SNE Effectively guide for determining how to tune my model.

I also used this StackOverflow post to figure out how to plot thumbnails in t-SNE dimensions.

In [13]:

num_groups = np.shape(ims)[0]

#reshape data for t-SNE (1D array for each image instead of 2D)

images_tsne = np.zeros((num_groups, size*size))
for ii in range(num_groups):
    images_tsne[ii,:] = ims[ii].flatten()

In [18]:
#run t_SNE

tsne_model = manifold.TSNE(n_components=3,perplexity=50,learning_rate=400,n_iter=3000, 
                           init='pca', random_state=5, early_exaggeration=12)

print("Running T-SNE . . .")
t0 = time.time()
tsne_output = tsne_model.fit_transform(images_tsne)
print("Time to run TSNE: %.2fs" % (time.time() - t0))

The first dimension appears to represent the level to which the object fills the frame of the image, and the third dimension appears to encode the rotation angle of the object within the image. The second dimension is unclear in its visual representation.

GMM¶

Because the more abnormal images appeared to be closer to the edges of the distribution of images in the t-SNE plots, I implemented a Gaussian Mixture Model to score images based on their distance from the center of the distribution.

I used this example from the scikit-learn documentation for implementing a Gaussian mixture model.

In [23]:
clf = mixture.GaussianMixture(n_components=2, covariance_type='full')
clf.fit(tsne_output)
Out[23]:

                means_init=None, n_components=2, n_init=1, precisions_init=None,
                random_state=None, reg_covar=1e-06, tol=0.001, verbose=0,
                verbose_interval=10, warm_start=False, weights_init=None)
In [24]:
#score each image with model
#score is log-likelihood

scores = clf.score_samples(tsne_output)
tsne_df['score'] = scores
In [25]:
#copy data and sort by score (lowest is furthest from center of distribution)

preds = tsne_df.copy()
preds = preds.sort_values(by = 'score').reset_index()

#show only one version of each image (don't show multiple augmentations of the same one)
i = 0
already_shown = []
inds = []
while len(already_shown) < rows*cols:
    if preds['file'][i] in already_shown:
        pass
    else:
        already_shown.append(preds['file'][i])
        inds.append(i)
        
    i += 1
    
    
j = 0
for ax in axs:
    for a in ax:
        ind = preds['index'][inds[j]]
        a.set_title(preds['file'][inds[j]])
        a.imshow(data[ind])

        j += 1
